    "comment": "Rationale: Rab7 is a marker for late endosomes (Zerial and McBride, 2001. PMID:11252952)\n\n\"The inactivated synaptic vesicles must ultimately be degraded at a later time point. Synaptic vesicle degradation is widely assumed to entail fusion to the endo-lysosomal system (Katzmann et al, 2002; Raiborg & Stenmark, 2009; Rizzoli, 2014). To test whether the inactivated vesicles are indeed targeted for degradation, we tested their co-localization with the recycling endosome marker Rab7, which is thought to be the first step in vesicle degradation (Rizzoli, 2014). We took advantage of experiments in which SNAP25 or sypHy-SNAP25 was overexpressed, and found that the vesicles in both cases co-localized more strongly with Rab7 than control vesicles (Appendix Fig S30).\". Experimental description: M&M: \"Neuronal hippocampal cultures were obtained from dissociated hippocampi of newborn rats\"\n\nantibody:\n\"Rab7 (# 9367; Cell Signaling Technology, Cambridge, UK)\"\nnote; this is a monoclonal antibody against RAB7A.",
